^B@2hondo717: Some people play "steps" over 2@C, although I do not particularly care for them myself. If you play steps, then you show the number of "controls" you have. An ace is considered 2 controls, and a K is considered one.
For example, if responder has one ace and one k, he has 3 controls. Then, 2@D shows 0 or 1 control (no more than a K), 2@H shows 2 controls (one ace or 2 kings),  2@S shows 3 controls - specifically an ace and a K  and 2N shows 3 controls - specifically 3 kings. 3@C shows 4 or more controls, which rarely occurs. My problem with steps is they take up too much bidding room and I recommend you play 2@D waiting.|
