^d@e@2Fourth suit forcing (4SF) is a convention most experts play as a way of establishing @E@3a game forcing auction while keeping the bidding at a lower level. Although it is independent of the 2 Over 1 System and can be played as part of Standard American, I include a description here because it is based on the same principles.

It works as follows. Assume partner has opened a suit, you have responded in a different suit, and opener has bid a third suit. If you bid the only remaining suit (the 4th suit), that is an artificial bid which establishes a game forcing auction. It says nothing about the 4th suit, only that responder is unsure about where to play the hand, but wants to play in game. The partner may not pass below the game level, and responder's next bid clarifies why he made the fourth suit forcing call.

There are many reasons why responder would choose to bid 4sf. Here are some of the more common reasons: Responder's first suit was a 5 card major, and he would like to find out if opener has 3 card support. Since opener did not raise the major right away, he does not have four. But over 4SF, he can now raise responder's first suit with 3 card support.

Responder does not have good stoppers in the 4th suit, and is hoping opener will bid NT with astopper. Responder is interested in slam in one of opener's suit. He wants to establish a game forcing auction, and will then raise one of opener's suits (more often the second suit) with his next bid.

                                                 
