BG|6|BT||NT||CS|1|cp|4|HT|a|fp|1|3d|4|AT|
^-{                      FOURTH  SUIT  FORCING                  }
^-|
cp||
fp|2|
at| 
^d@e@2Responder has a good six card suit of his own with game forcing values. If he simply @E@3repeats his suit, opener can pass. By bidding 4th suit forcing and then bidding his suit, he can describe his hand and make sure the partnership gets to game.

Note that there is one other important implication if you play 4SF. If opener bids a suit, responder bids another suit, opener bids a third suit, and responder jumps in his original suit, that is no longer game forcing (although it is highly invitational). If responder had a game forcing hand, he would bid 4SF and then rebid his suit, So by failing to do so, he is showing an invitational hand with a long suit.

You may be concerned about hands where responder actually has the fourth suit, and be worried about missing a fit in that suit. However, that is not really a problem. First of all, it is fairly unlikely, because opener has already shown 2 suits, and it is unlikely he has good support for a third suit (unless he is 5-4-4 or 4-4-4-1). Second of all, opener is allowed to raise the fourth suit with 4 card support.


                                            
